                  <handDesc>
                     <!--ACHTUNG! first HandNote comes from writing system in Ethiospare. the others are one for each CHANGE OF HAND-->
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Mediocre.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (vivid scarlet, deep magenta).</seg>
                        <date>Second half of the 17th century</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ሰላ፡ or ሰ፡</abbr> for <expan>ሰላም፡ </expan> (in <locus from="47vb" to="49va">47vb-49va</locus>).</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Nomina sacra, name of the protagonist; incipit of
                           Text I (2 red lines: 1 red line alternating with 1 black line) and of
                           some of its sections (e.g. fols. 3vb, 35rb); word salām "salutation" and
                           its abbreviations; elements of the punctuation signs; elements of
                           Ethiopic numerals.&#xD; The name of the original donor, mentioned in the
                           supplication formulas, has been crudely erased and replaced with that of
                           Gabra Madḫǝn, written in deep magenta (e.g., fols. 8ra, 13rb, 18va,
                           35rb).</seg>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The script appears uneven, tending to
                        broadly spaced and irregularly slanted letters. A few distinctive features
                        of the handwriting appear throughout the
                        Ms.:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic"> - occasionally, the form of 'one' (፩,
                        triangular upwards-oriented, but with dashes) reminiscent of the archaic one
                        (e.g., <locus target="#12ra">12ra</locus>
                        l.2)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic"> - the characters ወ, መ, ሠ are often
                        formed on a slant, the lower left side extends to the base line while the
                        upper right part extends to the upper
                        limit<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic"> - in some cases the vowel marker of ሎ
                        is attached directly to the right leg at the upper part (e.g., <locus target="#8ra">8ra</locus> l.7, 18va l.
                        5)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic"> - ሮ, ሬ and ፌ are of peculiar shape
                        (e.g., fol 16ral. 9, 11,
                        14).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic"> - some letters show distinct hook
                        vowel markers (e.g., ስ and
                        ብ).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h8" script="Ethiopic"> The involvement of more than one
                        scribe cannot be excluded (cp. <locus target="#14">14</locus> and
                        15).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
